**Mission**

Our mission is to contribute to the overall wellness and development of society, and to provide quality social and educational services to families in our community.

**Vision**

The Reggio Emilia Montessori Center (REMC) is a learning community committed to supporting the development of young children. Our early childhood center employs a whole child approach to ensure that each student is engaged and challenged in a safe, stimulating, and supportive environment that promotes creativity, critical thinking, and kindness and respect for others. We are passionate about creating access to quality social services and reducing economic inequality in urban areas.

We are expanding our work in the South Bronx! We currently work with community members through the Bronx H.Y.P.E Family Enrichment Center. Family Enrichment Centers (FECs) are warm and welcoming community gathering places where any family or individual can come for support, information, and to participate in and/or lead activities (called “offerings”). FECs are based on the premise that community members design and drive the FEC’s activities or offerings. We are excited to further our mission through the implementation of the School-Based Early Support model in South Bronx public schools.

The Division of Prevention Services (DPS) in the New York City Administration for Children’s Services (ACS) is renaming and redesigning the programs formerly known as ACS Beacon Prevention. Through the redesign, ACS intends to offer families a menu of flexible service options that strive to connect families to community resources through case management, address families’ concrete needs, support parents/caregivers, and avoid unnecessary investigations. The Reggio Emilia Montessori Center will implement this model in public schools located in School Districts 7 and 12.

**Position Description: Associate Vice President (AVP) for Community Programs**

The Reggio Emilia Montessori Center is growing its leadership team and looking for like-minded individuals to join in our expansion. The Executive Leadership Team consists of the Executive Director, Associate Vice President for Community Programs, and HR and Finance Lead. The Associate Vice President for Community Programs oversees the general management of all community based programs, with a focus on supervisor coaching and support, culture, and program implementation and quality. The AVP for Community Programs will contribute to the overall strategy of the organization, represent the organization at external meetings, develop a deep understanding of programs, cultivate program leadership, and ensure workplace culture is positive. This role requires someone who is adept at problem solving, using strengths-based leadership approaches to develop teams, and understands the importance of data-driven decision making. The AVP for Community Programs is eligible for promotion to Vice President after three consecutive years of high performance in the AVP role. The Associate Vice President for Community Programs reports directly to the Executive Director.

**Title:** Associate Vice President for Community Programs

**Job Type:** Full-Time; Exempt

**Hours:** 30 hours/week; Hybrid with Mondays-Tuesdays Remote

**Schedule:** Mondays-Tuesdays 8:30am-1:00pm (Remote - Half Day Work Days); Wednesdays-Fridays 9:30am-4:30pm (On-Site)

**Work Location:** 111 Bruckner Blvd., Bronx, NY 10454; with travel to programs around NYC required

**Salary:** $75,000-$80,000 (30 hour Hybrid work week)

*Salary ranges represent the potential low and high end for the position. The salary offered would be based on, but not limited to, experience, education, budget, and demonstrated skills.*

**Specific responsibilities include but are not limited to:**

Leadership and Problem Solving

* Demonstrate kindness and warmth in your interactions with others;
* Represent the organization and conduct outreach at community events and venues;
* Deliver presentations and/or speeches at external and internal meetings;
* Maintain a sense of being approachable;
* Support the professional growth of staff;
* Serve as a role model for how to lead with humility and self awareness;
* Strategically plan ahead for tasks and responsibilities;
* Generate several solutions and next steps to address barriers or problems;
* Demonstrate the ability to be decisive, make collaborative decisions, and know which is best depending on circumstances;
* Plan for potential challenges, and respond quickly and calmly to the unexpected;
* Demonstrate grace and poise when problem solving and remain calm when faced with challenging situations;
* Consistently engage in self reflection and feedback solicitation;
* Take initiative in engaging in self development experiences;
* Demonstrate value for others and understand that each leader is an asset and resource;
* Serve as an example of outstanding leadership and professionalism.

Managing and Supporting Others

* Visit programs to engage in conversations and interactions with the purpose of building rapport and strengthening relationships;
* Ensure each leader is engaged in their work and supported in their development;
* Set clear expectations for program leaders;
* Observe staff engaging with coworkers, supervisors, community members and clients;
* Communicate feedback and next steps positively and constructively;
* Develop and strengthen leadership skills of supervisors in line with organization core values and strengths-based approaches;
* Coach leaders to delegate effectively, demonstrate patience, understand the importance of making time to listen to staff, and prioritize workplace culture;
* Motivate leaders to meet program goals and expectations;
* Coordinate team building opportunities on a program and organization-wide level;
* Navigate challenging conversations respectfully and gracefully;
* Facilitate mediation and conflict-resolution meetings as needed;
* Complete hiring and termination procedures;
* Be available to respond to site emergencies requiring executive level personnel and travel to a site location in 60 minutes or less on weekdays, including unexpected weekend emergencies.

Program Quality and Improvement

* Collaborate with Quality Assurance personnel in the development and implementation of quality assurance measures;
* Take initiative in developing and implementing new systems and procedures aimed at improving program quality or efficiency;
* Create and facilitate workshops and trainings to support new hire orientation or respond to program needs;
* Facilitate staff reflections and conduct staff evaluations;
* Provide regular feedback to supervisors and program leaders;
* Develop and implement performance improvement plans to support staff performance;
* Conduct weekly, biweekly and monthly team meetings;
* Follow up on tasks and directives given, and ensure a smooth follow-through from beginning to end;
* Follow through on promises and commitments.

Administrative

* Demonstrate a high level of organization and develop clear systems to manage time and tasks;
* Communicate policies, requirements, and performance targets to staff;
* Ensure that all program, participant and client files are kept in compliance with organization, funder and city standards;
* Complete written reports required by state and city agencies and partners;
* Complete grant and funding applications;
* Complete other duties as assigned and required.

**Minimum Qualifications**

* Must be approachable and patient with all employees;
* Must be highly reflective on one’s words and actions;
* Must be calm in challenging situations;
* Must maintain poise at all times;
* Must have outstanding attention to detail;
* Must have outstanding verbal and written communication skills;
* Must be proficient in Google Documents and Google Sheets;
* Must be able to lift 50lbs;
* Must be able to travel around NYC weekly;
* Must be able to perform multiple tasks effectively in a fast-paced, challenging, and constantly changing environment;
* Bachelor’s Degree; Master’s Degree Preferred;
* At least three (3) years of non-profit or CBO administrative experience;
* At least two (2) years of supervisory experience;
* At least two (2) years of experience coaching staff or developing teams;
* and families;

**Preferred Qualifications**

* Master’s Degree;
* At least four (4) years of non-profit or CBO administrative experience;
* At least three (3) years of supervisory experience;
* At least three (3) years of experience coaching staff or developing teams;
* At least five (5) years of relevant experience living and/or working in the South Bronx;
* Bilingual: Spanish/English

Submission of a resume is not a guarantee that you will receive an interview. Only those candidates under consideration will be contacted.

The Reggio Emilia Montessori Center is committed to a diverse workforce, and we seek diversity among applicants for this position. People of color, women, gay/lesbian/bisexual/transgender people, people with disabilities, and veterans are encouraged to apply.

**The Reggio Emilia Montessori Center is an Equal Employment Opportunity Employer**

